{
  "texts": [
    "This is a classical result, see, e.g., [26].Proposition 1.",
    "Under Assumption 2, T is a Hilbert-Schmidt operator and thus compact.Proof.",
    "Take (e i) i≥1 any orthonormal basis (ONB) of L 2 (X).",
    "Then, using the definition of the Hilbert-Schmidt norm:∥T ∥ 2 HS = i≥1 ∥T e i ∥ 2 L2(Z)(definition of HS norm via ONB)= i≥1 Z |T e i (z)| 2 dπ Z (z) (expand L 2 (Z) norm) = i≥1 Z ⟨e i, p(•, z)⟩ 2 L2(X) dπ Z (z)(by Eq.",
    "( 14))= Z i≥1 ⟨e i, p(•, z)⟩ 2 L2(X) dπ Z (z) (Fubini's theorem) = Z ∥p(•, z)∥ 2 L2(X) dπ Z (z) (Parseval's identity) = X ×Z p(x, z) 2 dπ X (x) dπ Z (z) (expand L 2 norm) < +∞ (by Assumption 2, since p ∈ L 2 (π X ⊗ π Z)).Note that the proof shows in addition that ∥T ∥ HS = ∥p∥ L2(π X ⊗π Z)."
  ]
}